In article <strnlghtCtyt8E.JBA@netcom.com>
           david@sternlight.com "David Sternlight" writes:

> In article <CtyHAy.AJ8@cix.compulink.co.uk>,
> Andrew Haley <aph@cix.compulink.co.uk> wrote:
> >
> >But there is a crucial difference between a process patent and an
> >algorithm patent; the former transforms matter in some way, the latter
> >does not.
> 
> Could be. The RSA patent is, under this definition a process patent because
> it transforms the characters/bits/electrons of a plaintext message into
> those of the encrypted one and vice-versa. That's why it is valid even where
> "algorithm" patents are not, having been written in terms of a
> system/process patent.

But this is all *any* computer program does, and computer programs are
specifically excluded from patentability.

